Installing Homebrew on the MaC ---

  harshwardhan_baghel@Harshwardhans-MacBook-Air ~ % history
    1  brew update
    2  ls /opt/homebrew/bin/brew || ls /usr/local/bin/brew
    3  /bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/HEAD/install.sh)"
    4  brew --version
    5  echo >> /Users/harshwardhan_baghel/.zprofile
    6  echo 'eval "$(/opt/homebrew/bin/brew shellenv zsh)"' >> /Users/harshwardhan_baghel/.zprofile
    7  eval "$(/opt/homebrew/bin/brew shellenv zsh)"
    8  brew help
    9  brew --version

Important Brew commands ----

    brew search [package]: Search for a tool. (e.g., brew search python)
    brew install [package]: The heavy lifter. Downloads and installs the tool.
    brew info [package]: Shows you details about a tool (its version, website, and requirements) before you install it.

    brew update: Updates Homebrew itself and the list of available software (the "map").
    brew upgrade: Actually updates the software you’ve installed to the latest versions.

    brew list: Shows everything you have installed via Brew.
    brew uninstall [package]: Removes a tool you no longer need.
    brew cleanup: Deletes old versions and "leftover" files from previous installs. It’s like taking out the trash.

    brew doctor: This scans your system for common problems and tells you exactly how to fix them. It is the first thing you should do if something goes wrong.

    brew install --cask vlc: Installs the VLC Media Player.
    brew install --cask visual-studio-code: Installs VS Code.

Install Minicube/Kubernetes ----

    Homebrew (the installer)
    OrbStack (the engine)
    Minikube (the cluster manager)
    Kubectl (the remote control)

    brew install minicube kubectl: it will install minicube on system
    brew install --cask orbstack: installs OrbStack, which is a fast, light, and modern replacement for Docker Desktop.
      What does it actually install?
        When you run that command, Homebrew downloads the OrbStack application and sets up the following:
          The OrbStack GUI: A dashboard where you can see your running containers, Kubernetes nodes, and Linux machines.
          Docker CLI Tools: It installs (or links) the standard docker, docker-compose, and buildx commands so you can use them in your terminal just like you would with Docker Desktop.
          A Virtualization Engine: It sets up a highly optimized Linux kernel that runs natively on macOS's virtualization framework.
          Local Domain Names: It automatically gives your containers local URLs (like my-app.orb.local), so you don't have to mess with IP addresses.
    brew install docker: install docker first on top od OrbStack
    Then start Docker from OrbStack application
    docker ps: to see what's riunning on docker
    minikube start --driver=docker: telling Minikube to build a miniature using Docker, one-node data center inside your Mac.

Work on Minicube ----
    kubectl get nodes: current state and metadata of all registered Node objects in the cluster.
    minikube status: to check minikube running status.

Kubectl Commands ----
    kubectl get pods: check the pods inside the node
    kubectl get services: check the services 
    kubectl create -h: It will give all available create commands
      clusterrole           Create a cluster role
      clusterrolebinding    Create a cluster role binding for a particular cluster role
      configmap             Create a config map from a local file, directory or literal value
      cronjob               Create a cron job with the specified name
      deployment            Create a deployment with the specified name
      ingress               Create an ingress with the specified name
      job                   Create a job with the specified name
      namespace             Create a namespace with the specified name
      poddisruptionbudget   Create a pod disruption budget with the specified name
      priorityclass         Create a priority class with the specified name
      quota                 Create a quota with the specified name
      role                  Create a role with single rule
      rolebinding           Create a role binding for a particular role or cluster role
      secret                Create a secret using a specified subcommand
      service               Create a service using a specified subcommand
      serviceaccount        Create a service account with the specified name
      token                 Request a service account token
    kubectl create deployment NAME --image=image: to create deplyment using certain docker image [nginx-depl --image=nginx].
    kubectl get deployment: check the deployment
    ImagePullBackOff:  is the system's way of saying: "I tried to download the software for your Pod, but I failed, and I’m tired of trying for a moment."
    minikube start/stop: to start and stop the minikube.
    kubectl get replicaset: 
    kubectl edit deployment nginx-depl: let us edit the deployment
    kubectl logs podName: get the logs of pod to debug
    kubectl describe podName: get the deatiled execution flow and status
    kubectl exec -it PodName -- bin/bash: It allows you to open an interactive terminal session inside the running Pod.
    exit: to exit from terminal.
    kubectl delete deployment mongo-depl: delete the deployment.
    kubectl apply -f config-file.yaml: It will apply the changes to configuration file.
    kubectl get namespaces: get the existing namespaces
      Namespace	                       Purpose
      default	              Where resources go if no namespace is specified
      kube-system	          Kubernetes system components
      kube-public	          Publicly readable data
      kube-node-lease	      Node heartbeat information
    kubectl create namespace dev: create namespace for dev environment
    

    
